<TITLE> Bracing for a diarrhoea outbreak </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 12 (bdnews24.com)  Doctors are not expecting critical diarrhoea outbreak soon despite a regular flow of about 500 patients per day. Due to the late arrival of monsoon last year, the diarrhoea outbreak reached epidemic proportions with up to 1500 new patients every day. Diarrhoea outbreak is a recurring phenomenon during April-May the end of spring after a long dry spell just before the monsoons arrive. The doctors, however, said they were fully prepared. Azharul Islam, a doctor of ICDDRBDhaka, told bdnews24.com on Friday that although the outbreak occurred around April-May, it seems to have started earlier this year. "Other than this, there are problems with water in the water of many areas." "At the current rate, the situation cannot be deemed critical. However if needs arise, we have preparations to set up another 1,000 beds for emergency purposes. Currently there are 550 beds, including tents, in the diarrhoea ward," the doctor said. Of the diarrhoea patients arriving on Friday, there were many from Badda, Dembra-Jatrabari and Mirpur, according to the staff. They also said that the number of ill children was comparatively higher than that of the adults. Between 12am and 3pm on Friday, 321 patients were admitted. On Thursday the number was 495, on Wednesday 512 and on Tuesday it was 520. bd
